<h3 id="factors">Factors</h3>
<p>In statistical analysis, we might want to represent categorical variables in a data structure. In other languages, we might construct them using <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">enums</code> and represent categories as constant integers. R has a way of expressing <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">enums</code> with simpler implementation â€“ we call it a Factor.</p>

<p>Letâ€™s see how we can construct, and make simple operations in this data structure:</p>

<ul>
  <li>The Syntax for constructing Factors: <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">âŸ¨variable_nameâŸ©&lt;-factor(âŸ¨vectorâŸ©)</code>.
    <div class="language-R highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="o">&gt;</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">blood_type</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="nf">c</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">"A"</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">"B"</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="s2">"O"</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="s2">"O"</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="s2">"A"</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="s2">"B"</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="s2">"AB"</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="s2">"AB"</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="w">
